\begin_inset Formula $(2,2)$
\end_inset

, we therefore have 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{4}(S)=\text{the purple square}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}(S)=\text{the orange square}$
\end_inset

 (the bottom left square of the dissection); 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}(S)=\text{the blue square}$
\end_inset

 (the top left square of the dissection); and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{3}(S)=\text{the green square}$
\end_inset

 (the top right square of the dissection).
 Altogether, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{1}(S)\cup T_{2}(S)\cup T_{3}(S)\cup T_{4}(S)=S.\label{eq:hutchinson-square}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A theorem of Hutchinson
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hutchinson"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 asserts that 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is the only compact set with this property.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1},T_{2},T_{3},T_{4}$
\end_inset

