\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 via equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:hutchinson-square"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 These four transformations provide a complete description of the square
 with opposite corners at 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(2,2)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A special case of Hutchinson's theorem states that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}=\{C_{1},C_{2},\ldots,C_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is any set of similtudes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 with scale factors less than one, then there is exactly one compact set
 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{C}}(K)=K$
\end_inset

 where, for any subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{C}}$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{C}}(A)=C_{1}(A)\cup C_{2}(A)\cup\cdots\cup C_{n}(A).\label{eq:hutchinson-operator}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Moreover, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{k\to\infty}\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{C}}^{\circ k}(A)=K
\]

\end_inset

for any compact set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Not only does the theorem assert the existence and uniqueness of the set
 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, it gives a way to construct it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Applying this theorem to the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}=\{T_{1},T_{2},T_{3},T_{4}\}$
